# Register and manage your service

You get a unique client ID when you register your service. You'll need this client ID to integrate each of your services with GOV.UK One Login. 

You should configure a client ID for each environment you have. For example, if you have staging, user acceptance testing, integration and production you should configure 4 client IDs. There's further [guidance on creating a configuration for each service you're integrating][integrate.client-id].

Registering should take 5 minutes to complete. To register your service to use GOV.UK One Login, you'll need:

* a government email address
* a mobile phone

If you do not have a government email address or mobile phone, you should find a civil servant in your team who can register the service on your behalf.

Whoever registers the service will have the entry tied to their email address. It is currently not possible to reassign ownership if someone leaves or to add multiple email addresses to a particular client. If you need access after someone has left, you can create an additional client using a different email address and transfer the configuration settings to the new account. 

1. Go to the [Get started with GOV.UK One Login][external.get-started-gov-uk-one-login] page and select *Create admin tool account*.
1. Follow the on-screen instructions to enter your email address and confirm your email security code.
1. Enter your mobile number and confirm your mobile security code.
1. Fill in your client configuration details using this table. 

| Name | Field name | Description |
| --- | --- | --- |
| [Client ID](#client-id) | `ClientID` | Your unique client ID. You must configure this into your service. |
| [Client name (Service name)](#client-name) | `ClientName` | The name of your service, visible to users in the sign in journey. |
| [Client type](#client-type) | `ClientType` | The type of client. This is always `web`. |
| [Contacts](#contacts) | `Contacts` | Email addresses of your service's technical contacts. |
| [Cookie consent shared](#cookie-consent-shared) | `CookieConsentShared` | Whether cookie consent is shared. This is always `false`. |
| [Identity verification supported](#identity-verification-supported) | `IdentityVerificationSupported` | Whether your service uses identity verification. |
| [Redirect URLs](#redirect-urls) | `RedirectUrls` | The URL we return your user to after they complete their journey. |
| [Post-logout URLs](#post-logout-urls) | `PostLogoutRedirectUrls` | URLs to redirect your users to after they log out. |
| [Back channel logout URI](#back-channel-logout-uri) | `BackChannelLogoutUri` | The endpoint GOV.UK One Login calls to send logout notifications. |
| [Landing page URL](#landing-page-url) | `LandingPageUrl` | The page users are redirected to after their in-person identity check. |
| [Sector identifier URI](#sector-identifier-uri) | `SectorIdentifierUri` | Your service's sector identifier. |
| [Scopes](#scopes) | `Scopes` | The scopes your service needs. You must include `openid`. |
| [Claims](#claims) | `Claims` | The claims your service requests from GOV.UK One Login. |
| [Token authentication method](#token-authentication-method) | `TokenAuthMethod` | Either `private_key_jwt` or `client_secret_post`. |
| [Public key](#public-key) | `PublicKey` | Needed if using `private_key_jwt` or a signed authorisation request (JAR). |
| [ID token signing algorithm](#id-token-signing-algorithm) | `IdTokenSigningAlgorithm` | Either `RS256` or `ES256`. Defaults to `ES256`. |
