## Client ID

Your client ID is unique to your service and is created when you register. You must configure this into your service to make requests to GOV.UK One Login.

You cannot change your client ID. If you need a new one, you must register a new client.

## Client name

Choose your client name.

The client name appears in the user interface when GOV.UK One Login redirects your user back to your service so choose something your users would recognise.

There's further [guidance on naming your service][external.service-manual-naming].

## Client type

The client type is always `web`. You cannot change this value.

## Contacts

Enter the email addresses of your service's technical contacts. This can be a group email or multiple separate email addresses, or a combination of both.

GOV.UK One Login uses these to notify your team about service changes or incidents.

## Cookie consent shared

Cookie consent shared is always `false`. You cannot change this value.

## Identity verification supported

Set this to `true` if your service uses GOV.UK One Login to prove your users' identities. Set this to `false` if your service only uses authentication.

## Redirect URLs

Enter one or more of your service's redirect URLs. These are the URLs GOV.UK One Login returns your user to after they complete their journey.

## Post-logout URLs

If you want to redirect your users after they log out, enter one or more URLs. These are where you redirect your users to after you have logged them out.

There's further guidance on [logging your user out of GOV.UK One Login][integrate.managing-sessions-logout].

## Back channel logout URI

Specify the URI of the endpoint you want GOV.UK One Login to call when sending logout notifications to your service.

There's further guidance on [requesting logout notifications from GOV.UK One Login][integrate.managing-sessions-backchannel-logout].

## Landing page URL

`LandingPageUrl` is only needed if you are making identity requests. Users will be redirected to this landing page after their in-person identity check.

There's further guidance on [helping your users after their in-person identity check][integrate.in-person-identity-checks].

Send an email to [govuk-one-login@digital.cabinet-office.gov.uk](mailto:govuk-one-login@digital.cabinet-office.gov.uk) if you need to configure this.

## Sector identifier URI

You must not change the sector identifier once your service has started to sign up or migrate users. Doing this will change the subject IDs GOV.UK One Login creates for each individual user.

There's further [guidance on choosing your sector identifier][integrate.choose-sector-id].

If your service has more than one `redirect_uri`, you must set the sector identifier in line with the [OpenID Connect Core 1.0 specification][external.oidc-connect-core-pairwise-algorithm].

## Scopes

Enter the scopes your service needs. You must include the `openid` scope.

You may choose one or more of the following:

- `email`
- `phone`

There's further [guidance on choosing which user attributes your service can request][integrate.choose-request-scope].

## Claims

If you’re doing identity verification, you’ll need to specify which claims your service requires.

You can choose one or more of the following:

- `https://vocab.account.gov.uk/v1/passport`
- `https://vocab.account.gov.uk/v1/drivingPermit`
- `https://vocab.account.gov.uk/v1/address`
- `https://vocab.account.gov.uk/v1/coreIdentityJWT`
- `https://vocab.account.gov.uk/v1/returnCode`

We recommend also including `https://vocab.account.gov.uk/v1/returnCode` to make your error handling clearer. 

There's further [guidance on return codes][integrate.return-codes].

If you're requesting identity verification, you must include: `https://vocab.account.gov.uk/v1/coreIdentityJWT`

There's further guidance on [choosing which claims your service can request][integrate.choose-request-claim].

## Token authentication method

Specify the token authentication method your service is using. This will be `private_key_jwt` or `client_secret_post`.

There's further [guidance on using the correct token authentication method for your service][integrate.choose-correct-token-auth-method].

## Public key

To provide your public keys via a JWKS endpoint (strongly recommended for production) set the **Key source** to the JWKs URL and provide the URL for your publicly available JWKS endpoint.

To provide a static public key, set the **Key source** to Static key and enter the contents of your public key Privacy Enhanced Mail (PEM) file (or whichever file was created when you created your key pair).

There's further [guidance on creating a key pair][integrate.generate-key-pair].

## ID token signing algorithm

By default, GOV.UK One Login signs the `id_token` JSON Web Token (JWT) using the `ES256` algorithm but some third-party tooling does not support `ES256`. If your service needs an alternative algorithm, we can sign your `id_token` JWT using the `RS256` algorithm.

## JAR validation required

This is always `false` by default. You cannot change this value.

## One Login service

This is always `false`. You cannot change this value.

## PKCE enforced

Specify whether your service must provide the parameters needed for Proof Key for Code Exchange (PKCE) protocol in the [authorize][integrate.make-authorize-request] and [token][integrate.make-token-request] requests.

You can [read more about PKCE in RFC 7636](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc7636).

## Subject type

The subject type is always `pairwise`. You cannot change this value.

## Service type

The service type is always `MANDATORY`. You cannot change this value.

## Test client

This is always `false`. You cannot change this value. *Internal use only*

